Package management with apt and d-n-f.

On linux you install software through a package manager, a tool that downloads software from a repository, works out and installs all the dependencies it needs, and keeps track of everything so it can be cleanly removed later. There are two major families. The debian and ubuntu world uses dot-deb packages, with apt as the modern command-line tool and d-p-k-g as the lower-level one underneath. The red hat world, including fedora, alma, and rocky, uses dot-r-p-m packages, with d-n-f as the modern command and r-p-m underneath.

The good news is that the vocabulary maps almost one-to-one between the two, so learning one teaches you most of the other. On the debian side, the day starts with apt update, which refreshes the catalog of available packages, and this step is important to do first. Then apt upgrade applies available updates. Apt install adds one or more packages, apt remove takes a package away while keeping its configuration, and apt purge removes the configuration too. To explore, apt search looks for packages by keyword and apt show displays the details of one. On the red hat side the equivalents are almost identical words: d-n-f upgrade, install, remove, search, and info, with the catalog refresh happening automatically rather than as a separate step.

A few extra commands are worth knowing on both. There is a way to find out which package owns a particular file on disk, an auto-remove command that cleans up dependencies no longer needed by anything, and a clean command that clears the cache of downloaded package files. The red hat tool also keeps a transaction history and can undo a past transaction, a genuinely useful safety net when an update causes trouble. For the exam, be fluent in the apt verbs and know that each has a direct d-n-f counterpart.
